title: 2020 United States presidential election in Arizona
2020 United States presidential election in Arizona
added: Biden became the first Democrat to win Arizona since [[Bill Clinton]]'s victory in the [[1996 United States presidential election]], and only the second since [[1948 United States presidential election in Arizona|1948]]. He is also the first Democrat to win [[Maricopa County]] since [[Harry Truman]] in [[1948 United States presidential election in Arizona|1948]]<ref>https://www.newsweek.com/arizona-joe-biden-donald-trump-truman-maricopa-county-1547143</ref>, winning it by a margin of 2.2%, or 45,109 votes.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/11/03/us/elections/results-arizona.html</ref> Biden also became the first Democrat to break 47% of the vote since [[1948 United States presidential election in Arizona|1948]].

Some Republicans, such as Florida Representative [[Matt Gaetz]], have come to attribute Trump's loss to the unpopularity of Governor [[Doug Ducey]], and Senator [[Martha McSally]].<ref>https://twitter.com/mattgaetz/status/1324050314065072132?s=20</ref> A large part of the reason as to why Biden won the state, however, can be attributed to how he leaned into his friendship with the late Senator [[John McCain]] in fundraising, and received an endorsement from McCain's widowed wife, [[Cindy McCain]]<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2020/09/22/us/politics/cindy-mccain-endorsement-biden-trump.html</ref>, as well as changing demographics.<ref>https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/democrats-arizona-appealing-moderates-states-demographics-continue-change/story?id=73075957</ref>
